  doi = {10.1126/science.1208336},
  abstract = {We present a reference, comprehensive, high-resolution, digital mosaic of ice motion in Antarctica assembled from multiple satellite interferometric synthetic-aperture radar data acquired during the International Polar Year 2007 to 2009. The data reveal widespread, patterned, enhanced flow with tributary glaciers reaching hundreds to thousands of kilometers inland over the entire continent. This view of ice sheet motion emphasizes the importance of basal-slip\textendash dominated tributary flow over deformation-dominated ice sheet flow, redefines our understanding of ice sheet dynamics, and has far-reaching implications for the reconstruction and prediction of ice sheet evolution. A high-resolution map of ice motion in Antarctica shows the details of ice movement in a warming climate. A high-resolution map of ice motion in Antarctica shows the details of ice movement in a warming climate.},
